valueDomain.name: nhsNumber
valueDomain.description:
Http://www.datadictionary.nhs.uk/data_dictionary/attributes/n/nhs/nhs_number_de.asp?query=nhs%20number&rank=100&shownav=1
The NHS NUMBER, the primary identifier of a PERSON, is a unique identifier for a PATIENT within the NHS in England and Wales. This will not vary by any ORGANISATION of which a PERSON is a PATIENT. It is mandatory to record the NHS NUMBER. There are exceptions, such as Accident and Emergency care, sexual health and major incidents, as defined in existing national policies.
The NHS NUMBER is 10 numeric digits in length. The tenth digit is a check digit used to confirm its validity. The check digit is validated using the Modulus 11 algorithm and the use of this algorithm is mandatory. There are 5 steps in the validation of the check digit. Further guidance is available from the Health and Social Care Information Centre website.

model.name: Sample Information
model.description: The GMC laboratory will provide a set of sample metadata, and a set of test results, for each sample successfully processed. The complete set should be supplied at or before the time at which the derived products for example, the extracted DNA are dispatched to the Genomics England Biorepository. If the sample is held at the GMC laboratory for longer than 14 days, pending completion of a tumour-normal pair, then the GMC laboratory should provide an interim version of the sample metadata, together with any test results to date: information pertaining to the dispatch of derived products will not be available, and need not be supplied.

model.name: Core Clinical Data
model.description: All of the core data items provided following registration correspond to items in a specific longitudinal record model, in which each piece of data reported is associated with a date, usually the date of a relevant clinical event: an investigation, a diagnosis, or an intervention. The core data required for a cancer participant consists of data on relevant events in the existing medical history, and should be supplied within six weeks of sample collection.

model.name: Diagnosis
model.description: All of the core data item should be provided for every diagnosis. For each recorded diagnosis, the following essential data items are required.

dataElement.name: Event Reference
dataElement.description: Local Reference to Event. Must be unique within each site

dataElement.name: Organisation ID
dataElement.description: The ORGANISATION CODE of the ORGANISATION acting as a Health Care Provider for the event. This is the Organisation responsible for the investigation. For Imaging this relates to CR0310 this is the ORGANISATION SITE CODE of the Organisation where the imaging took place.

dataElement.name: Event Date
dataElement.description: This is the date of the event being reported: respectively the referral date, the date any imaging or pathology investigation occurred, the diagnosis date, the date a care plan was decided or any clinical intervention was made, or the patient admitted for clinical intervention

dataElement.name: Primary Diagnosis
dataElement.description: The ICD code for the primary diagnosis. PRIMARY DIAGNOSIS (ICD PATHOLOGICAL) is the PRIMARY DIAGNOSIS based on the evidence from a pathological examination. Note that a patient might have a diagnosis of breast cancer but a lung metastasis has been supplied as (one of) the GEL samples. The ICD code for the breast cancer would be supplied. model.name: Additional Data
model.description: The additional data required for a cancer participant includes data on all relevant events following registration, recorded against the same data model as that set out for core data in Section 3 above. It includes also the complete reporting data supplied by the GMC organisation against the Systemic Anti Cancer Therapy (SACT), Radiotherapy (RTDS), and Cancer Outcomes and Services (COSD) Datasets. All of this data should be supplied on a monthly basis.

relationshipType.name: base
relationshipType.sourceToDestination: Any catalogue element can be base for multiple elements of the same type.
relationshipType.destinationToSource: Any catalogue element can be based on multiple elements of the same type. Value domains will first use rules of the base value domains and than their owns when validating input values.

relationshipType.name: classification
relationshipType.sourceToDestination: Classification can classify multiple elements. Based on this relationship you can narrow the elements shown in the catalogue using the classifications filter in the bottom left corner. When classification is finalized all classified elements are finalized as well.
relationshipType.destinationToSource: Any element can be classified by multiple classifications. When new draft of the classified element is created then drafts for classifications are created as well.

relationshipType.name: containment
relationshipType.sourceToDestination: Model can contain multiple data elements. Contained data elements are finalized when the model is finalized.
relationshipType.destinationToSource: Data element can be contained in multiple models. When new draft of the data element is created then drafts for all containing models are created as well.

relationshipType.name: hierarchy
relationshipType.sourceToDestination: Model can contain (be parent of) multiple models. Child models are finalized when parent model is finalized,
relationshipType.destinationToSource: Model can be contained (be child model) in multiple models. When draft is created for child model drafts for parent models are created as well.

relationshipType.name: relatedTo
relationshipType.sourceToDestination: Any element can be related to multiple elements. This relationship has no specific meaning.

relationshipType.name: synonym
relationshipType.sourceToDestination: Any element can be synonym of multiple elements of the same type having similar meaning.
